<p>In this example, the given equation is  expressed implicitly. 
However, formulas for differentials can be used to obtain the derivative of a variable,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	d\br{x^2+y^2} &amp;= d\br{9} \\
	2x\,dx +2y\,dy &amp;= 0 \\
	2y\,dy &amp;= -2x\,dx
\end{align*}\]

<p>Then, rearranging the differentials, we obtain,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	\dydx &amp;= -\frac{\cancel{2}x}{\cancel{2}y} \\
	&amp;= -\frac{x}{y}		\tagans
\end{align*}\]

